article.description:
Deanna Nolan scored 26 points as the
Detroit Shock won a WNBA playoff series for the first time, beating
the Cleveland Rockers 77-63 in Game 3 Tuesday night.
article.headline: Shock advance to face Sun in East finals
article.linkText: Shock top Rockers for spot in East finals
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Deanna Nolan was embarrassed after
making just three of 17 shots in Sunday's playoff loss to the
Cleveland Rockers.

Nolan and her Detroit Shock teammates were feeling a different
emotion on Tuesday night.

Nolan scored 26 points, including 16 in the first six minutes,
and the Shock won their first playoff series with a 77-63 victory
in Game 3.

"The game on Sunday really upset us," said Nolan, whose six
3-pointers were one short of Mwadi Mabika's postseason record. "We
were very emotional tonight, because we knew how badly we played on
Sunday. This feels pretty good."

The top-seeded Shock advance to the Eastern Conference finals
against third-seeded Connecticut. Game 1 is in Connecticut on
Friday night with the next two in the best-of-three series at the
Palace on Sunday and Monday.

"Our goal this year was to make it to the WNBA Finals, and we
are halfway there," Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said. "Our focus
tonight was incredible -- you could tell at 11 this morning that we
wanted to play the game right then. These ladies wanted to make up
for what happened in Game 2, and they did."

Swin Cash added 14 points and Ruth Riley 11 for Detroit. Rookie
Cheryl Ford finished with 15 rebounds, including a league-record 10
defensive boards in the first half.

Chasity Melvin led Cleveland with 19 points, and Penny Taylor
added 17.

"I don't think we were focused at the beginning of the game,
and that is what has killed us all year," Melvin said. "There's
just no excuse for not being ready for Game 3 of a playoff series.
You shouldn't need an inspirational speech for a game like this."

Detroit took a 23-10 lead behind Nolan's 6-for-6 shooting in the
first six minutes. She made four 3-pointers in the streak, tying a
league playoff record for a half.

"Once I hit the first two or three shots, I knew I had a pretty
good rhythm going," she said. "I just didn't want to force things
-- we were playing so well that I knew I could let the game come to
me."

Despite having their starters on the bench for much of the half,
the Shock led by as many 20 points before taking a 42-24 lead into
the break. Eight Detroit players scored in the half.

"I thought our team played a very good series, but we had one
bad half," Cleveland coach Dan Hughes said. "This is why Detroit
played for the best record -- they wanted this game on their court.

"Those 16 points from Nolan were the biggest factor -- we dealt
with Detroit's other weapons, but we couldn't deal with her."

The Shock removed any lingering doubts by scoring the first
eight points of the second half to go up by 26. Nolan finished the
run with her fifth 3-pointer of the game, making her 6-for-7 from downtown for
the night. She finished 10-for-13 from the field.

"Last year, after a game like Sunday, Deanna would have quit
shooting," Laimbeer said. "Tonight, though, she kept looking for
her shot, and when she gets hot like she did tonight, she'll drain
everything."

Nolan was looking to Connecticut and beyond.

"Tonight, we showed just what we are capable of doing," she
said. "If we keep playing like this, we are the WNBA champions. No
doubt about it."
